You can check this great post: [Approaching a Xamarin.Android Bindings Case](https://gist.github.com/JonDouglas/dda6d8ace7d071b0e8cb#approaching-a-xamarinandroid-bindings-case), by checking the [Adding Types](https://gist.github.com/JonDouglas/dda6d8ace7d071b0e8cb#adding-types) part, it uses `&lt;add-node&gt;` when we want to add a class, change a constructor, or switch a generic type. 

For your lib, you can open the `Metadata.xml` under the `Transforms` folder, and then add this code:

    &lt;add-node path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;com.acrcloud.rec.sdk.utils&#39;]&quot;&gt;
      &lt;class abstract=&quot;false&quot; deprecated=&quot;not deprecated&quot; final=&quot;false&quot; name=&quot;ACRCloudLocalRecognizerInitAsyncTask&quot; static=&quot;true&quot; visibility=&quot;public&quot; extends=&quot;java.lang.Object&quot;&gt;
      &lt;/class&gt;
    
      &lt;class abstract=&quot;false&quot; deprecated=&quot;not deprecated&quot; final=&quot;false&quot; name=&quot;ACRCloudGetIPAddressAsyncTask&quot; static=&quot;true&quot; visibility=&quot;public&quot; extends=&quot;java.lang.Object&quot;&gt;
      &lt;/class&gt;
    &lt;/add-node&gt;

Then it can be successfully compiled, but I didn&#39;t test to reference this lib to Xamarin.Android project, you may need further research for using this lib. Anyway, that post helps a lot. 

You can also check the similar case on SO: [Java Binding Abstract class not being generated](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36648926/java-binding-abstract-class-not-being-generated).

    &lt;add-node path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;yourpPackageName&#39;]&quot;&gt;
       &lt;class abstract=&quot;false&quot; deprecated=&quot;not deprecated&quot; final=&quot;false&quot; name=&quot;YourClassName&quot; static=&quot;true&quot; visibility=&quot;public&quot; extends=&quot;java.lang.Object&quot;&gt; &lt;/class&gt;
&lt;/add-node&gt;

The other answers use a workaround that will only work in some cases. If you need the generated class to still extend AsyncTask, you can do this instead:

I was able to modify the method signature of DoInBackground to work correctly:

```
&lt;attr path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;$NAMESPACE&#39;]/class[@name=&#39;$CLASS&#39;]/method[@name=&#39;doInBackground&#39; and count(parameter)=1 and parameter[1][@type=&#39;java.lang.String...&#39;]]&quot; name=&quot;managedOverride&quot;&gt;override&lt;/attr&gt;
&lt;attr path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;$NAMESPACE&#39;]/class[@name=&#39;$CLASS&#39;]/method[@name=&#39;doInBackground&#39; and count(parameter)=1 and parameter[1][@type=&#39;java.lang.String...&#39;]]&quot; name=&quot;final&quot;&gt;true&lt;/attr&gt;
&lt;attr path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;$NAMESPACE&#39;]/class[@name=&#39;$CLASS&#39;]/method[@name=&#39;doInBackground&#39; and count(parameter)=1 and parameter[1][@type=&#39;java.lang.String...&#39;]]/parameter[1]&quot; name=&quot;managedType&quot;&gt;params Java.Lang.Object[]&lt;/attr&gt;
&lt;attr path=&quot;/api/package[@name=&#39;$NAMESPACE&#39;]/class[@name=&#39;$CLASS&#39;]/method[@name=&#39;doInBackground&#39; and count(parameter)=1 and parameter[1][@type=&#39;java.lang.String...&#39;]]&quot; name=&quot;managedReturn&quot;&gt;Java.Lang.Object&lt;/attr&gt;
```

The first two lines change virtual to override, the third line changes the parameter type and the fourth line changes the return type.

